<HEADLINE>
FT  17 OCT 94 / Letters to the Editor: A percentage of which market?
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr MICHAEL GOLDMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, Market definitions present notorious difficulties as is demonstrated by
the Pentos claim that Dillons at its low in June had a market share of 31.5
per cent ('Pentos Pounds 36m in the red after exceptional costs', October
12).
The annual value of the UK book market is some Pounds 2.5bn and Dillons'
sales cannot be more than Pounds 200m, which is 8 per cent. Even if the
market is defined more narrowly as consumer books, Pounds 200m equates to
about 12 per cent. What market definition produces a figure of more than
twice that level?
Michael Goldman,
1 Lyndale Close,
Blackheath, London SE3 7RG
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P5942 Book Stores.
</IN>
