<HEADLINE>
FT  17 OCT 94 / This Week: Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALKARIM JIVANI, TV Editor of Time Out
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
As the first British monarch sets foot on Russian soil, the most extensive
profile of her kinsman, Tsar Nicholas II, hits the screen. Network First
(Tuesday, 10.40-11.40pm, ITV) got access to personal papers, diaries,
photographs and archive footage which have never been aired. There are also
interviews with witnesses who may not live to tell their story again - one
is 112.
The first of a two-parter, this is an exhaustive study, introduced by Prince
Michael of Kent, who adds little to the programme apart from his uncanny
resemblance to his kinsman.
Insurance companies are accused of entrapment, intimidation and deception by
Dispatches (Wednesday, 9.00-9.45pm, C4), which investigates the ruses used
to avoid paying personal injury claims. The current affairs programme
interviews people who have had detectives prying into their lives by posing
as market researchers or simply by camping out in the front garden.
What are a high-ranking policeman's career choices when the attorney-general
instigates criminal charges against him? That's the question facing Tony
Clark with the return of the award-laden cop show Between The Lines
(Wednesday, 9.30-10.25pm, BBC1). Even prospective pub managers, security
guards and store detectives need references, and Clark doesn't have them. A
taut thriller with more twists and counter-twists than a helter-skelter.
Ford Transits claim half the British market for vans, but when they were
launched in 1965 - the first collaboration between Ford in Britain and its
German counterpart - they were considered outlandish and unsellable. A new
series, Perpetual Motion (Friday, 8.30-9.00pm, BBC2), looks at lovable
vehicles, starting with the Ford Transit - friend of burglars and police
patrols alike - and progressing to the Ferguson TE Tractor, Concorde and the
electric milk float.
The home of too many spoof chat shows launches a series that isn't a parody
of the genre with Last Word (Saturday, 11.00-11.45pm, BBC2). Hosted by
Germaine Greer, all the guests will be women, with contributions from Ann
Leslie, Suzanne Moore, Janet Street-Porter and Miranda Sawyer. Greer
promises to enrage and engage, and topics will include: 'What exactly are
women for?'
The highest-earning woman in the world, Madonna, meets the woman with the
lowest embarrasment threshold in Ruby Wax (Sunday, 10.05-10.35pm, BBC1).
With the shrewd pop singer hitting a run of bad luck in the last couple of
years, there is plenty to talk about. You can bet Wax won't hesitate to ask
the most probing posers.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
