<HEADLINE>
FT  17 OCT 94 / This Week: Film/Video
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIGEL ANDREWS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The question occupying most sensible UK filmgoers at present is: 'How do we
avoid seeing Forrest Gump even though all our friends are going?'
Here are some suggestions. Tell your friends you have it on good authority
(FT film critic) that Gump is a long, winsome, platitudinous piece of
Hollywoodiana. Then move smartly off in the direction of Pulp Fiction.
All the things said against Quentin Tarantino's Cannes Golden Palm-winning
thriller, opening this week, are true. It is violent, amoral, foul-mouthed
and drugs-obsessed, and, as a piece of action cinema, it makes the same
director's Reservoir Dogs look like Lady and the Tramp. In addition, its
mongrel cast - John Travolta, Bruce Willis, Uma Thurman, Harvey Keitel -
spend 2 1/2 hours trying to make sense of a four-stories-in-one screenplay.
But the things said for the film are also true. Tarantino has a gift for
black comedy unsurpassed in modern film-making and a wild pop-art eloquence
as a dialogue writer. Try the film yourself. If you are worried about what
to do with Aunt Edna, drop her off at Forrest Gump.
On no account let her stay at home with most of the new video releases. They
include the cheerfully OTT Mafia comedy Romeo Is Bleeding (Gary Oldman as a
violent Mob trouble-shooter) and the good-in-parts gothic gore fantasy
Necronomicon. But they also include the hauntingly beautiful Vietnamese film
The Scent Of Green Papaya. Tran Anh Hung's meditation-in-miniature on loss,
love and family,filmed entirely inside a French studio, was a hit of last
year's festival season. It is slow, sensual and lyrically-shot: a painting
come to life.
Other good news for Aunt Edna. The Client, opening this week, is a clean and
decent John Grisham thriller about a boy witness caught in a trial-room tug
of war. And that chaste and charming comedy, Four Weddings And a Funeral, is
still showing, having become the highest-earning British film ever (Dollars
200m worldwide). This means that all those subsidy-obsessed British film
people who keep crying out for lucrative grants now have one: Hugh Grant.
</TEXT>
