<HEADLINE>
FT  17 OCT 94 / 200 L&amp;G staff told to vie for 100 jobs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Legal &amp; General, one of Britain's biggest insurance companies, is in effect
sacking half its top life-products managers by asking all 200 of them to
re-apply for only 100 jobs.
The managers who survive the cull will be hired on new contracts. These will
tie remuneration to factors such as ability to cope with customer demands
and compliance with new insurance industry regulations, and not to sales
volumes.
The aim of the re-organisation, to take effect next month, is to emphasise
the company's commitment to a highly ethical method of selling pensions and
other life products after recent public criticism of life-industry sales
practices.
The changes come as the Securities and Investments Board, the City's chief
regulator, finishes drawing up a report which sets out mechanisms for
dealing with compensation claims from people who believe they were mis-sold
pensions in the late 1980s and early 1990s. It is thought claims across the
life industry will total at least Pounds 500m.
The company said its management changes were linked to the need to improve
standards among its managers and agents selling life products. It aimed to
keep 'the best people' from its 200 existing managers, who are based in
regional offices and who each typically supervise about 10 sales agents.
As part of the reorganisation it is greatly reducing opportunities for
managers to earn big sums from agents' sales.
Instead of their earnings being based partly on an 'override' of agents' own
sales commissions, these executives will have a basic salary of about Pounds
15,000. On top of this relatively small commissions will be paid, depending
on how well the managers satisfy customers' requirements in areas such as
collection of premiums and speed of reaction to inquiries.
The managers will also qualify for other commission payments, according to
how well they organise the recording of details about customers' financial
and personal circumstances when they are sold new products.
Such record keeping in the industry has been acknowledged to have been poor
in the past. Companies are having to improve in this area to meet tighter
consumer-protection regulations being introduced by the Personal Investment
Authority, the new regulator to protect private investors.
In the past insurance managers in some branches of the industry have been
able to earn more than Pounds 100,000 a year through 'sales override'.
Although estimates are difficult, it is thought that under the new
arrangements the company's managers will earn far less than this.
It is instituting its new arrangements for managers as part of a plan to
reduce the number of its sales agents. Unlike its managers, they are mainly
self-employed and paid commission only. The number of sales agents is
intended to fall from 2,300 at the beginning of the year to about 1,000 by
the end. In the late 1980s Legal and General had about 3,000 sales agents.
Announcing the company's latest financial results last month Mr David
Prosser, chief executive, said he saw little prospect of short-term
improvement in the difficult conditions of the UK market. He predicted
increased competition and narrower margins next year.
</TEXT>
