<HEADLINE>
FT  17 OCT 94 / Feltrim action to start this week
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS and JOHN MASON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The next chapter in the long-running Lloyd's of London legal saga opens this
week when more than 1,600 members of the insurance market start a fresh High
Court battle to win compensation for 1980s losses.
The Feltrim Names' Association hopes to repeat the success of the Gooda
Walker action group earlier this month. It won millions of pounds of damages
for losses by Names involved in 'spiral' insurance - by which underwriters
agreed to cover others for excessive losses from catastrophes.
The Feltrim association is claiming a total of Pounds 600m in three legal
cases.
The first, originally scheduled to start today but now not expected to get
under way until tomorrow, covers losses dating from between 1987 and 1989.
The case is the latest in a series of legal actions mounted by Lloyd's Names
which may stretch into the next century.
The Court of Appeal is expected to rule in the next few weeks whether Names
have a case for challenging Lloyd's legal right to reclaim money spent on
their behalf out of its central fund, which protects insurance policies for
Lloyd's clients. A victory for the Writs Response Group would hamper Lloyd's
attempts to claim an estimated Pounds 1.3bn outstanding from lossmaking
Names.
Even if the Names do not win outright the possibility of a further appeal to
the Lords and then the European Court could delay settlement of the amounts
outstanding for several years. Also expected soon is a decision by the
defendants in the Gooda Walker case on whether to appeal.
The Feltrim case centres on allegations that the professional Lloyd's
agencies involved in the catastrophe 'spiral' were negligent.
Names on Feltrim syndicates were badly hit by a succession of disasters
including the 1988 Piper Alpha oil platform accident.
The weight of legal action facing Lloyd's professional agencies has
increased the pressure for an out-of-court settlement.
Mr Colin Hook, chairman of the Feltrim Names' Association, said the Gooda
Walker judgment opened a 'window of opportunity' for such a deal - at least
for the 'spiral' cases.
He said many of the Names' action groups regarded a new settlement as the
most sensible route for Lloyd's, but added that 'if one thinks one is being
successful, the price goes up'.
</TEXT>
