<HEADLINE>
FT  17 OCT 94 / Feudal title holder claims Pounds 1bn slice of Jersey
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BILL BROWN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JERSEY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A private Jersey-based development company is using a feudal title to lay
claim to the industrial foreshore of St Helier, the island's capital,
estimated to be worth at least Pounds 1bn.
Les Pas Holdings claims it owns the most developed section of the foreshore,
including most of the island's busy harbour, the main power station, the
fuel farm, a new underpass and most of a big area of reclaimed land.
The claim is being vigorously contested by crown officers in Jersey, the
largest of the Channel Islands.
The figure at the centre of the bizarre wrangle is Advocate Richard Falle,
one of the island's leading lawyers and a director of Les Pas.
Eight years ago he and a group of businessmen submitted plans for a
commercial marina which they said would help alleviate the island's housing
problem and boost tourism.
The plan has been strongly opposed by conservationists, and a protest group
called Save Our Shoreline has mounted a sustained campaign to stop the
building of the marina.
At about the same time Les Pas also acquired the seigneur's feudal rights,
known as Le Fief de la Fosse. This includes rights over the foreshore that
traditionally extended as far as the seigneur could ride his horse into the
sea at low tide.
Mr Falle said he has become so frustrated by delays over the marina plan
that he is invoking the ancient title. 'I am bitterly disappointed with what
I believe to be politicking at every level,' he said.
'I still believe this scheme is the best and most constructive idea for the
development of Jersey's economy this century.'
The company claims its feudal rights over the foreshore include ownership.
Fiefdoms date back to Norman law and many landowners have fought similar, if
smaller cases in the UK.
Both Les Pas and the crown officers have commissioned leading QCs to
ascertain the validity of the feudal title claim, and Les Pas has registered
its claim with Jersey's Royal Court.
According to confidential committee documents, Mr Terry Sowden, a former
Jersey solicitor-general, advised the States, the island's parliament, that
Les Pas's claim had no foundation in law.
Miss Stephanie Nicolle, the present solicitor-general, has confirmed that if
Les Pas were to win, it would own everything built on the disputed territory
in perpetuity. In a letter to a senior civil servant, she warned: 'The
consequences of failure (by the authorities to win) do not bear
contemplation.'
Mr Falle said he is prepared to fight all the way to the European Court to
secure what he believes is Les Pas's rightful title. Senator Reg Jeune,
president of the States' policy and resources committee, Jersey's cabinet,
declined to comment.
In February the States approved a new Pounds 25m reclamation scheme on the
foreshore aimed at solving the island's waste-disposal problems, in spite of
the threat of possible court action against it over ownership.
</TEXT>
