<HEADLINE>
FT  17 OCT 94 / Portillo to shake up training scheme
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Michael Portillo, the employment secretary, has decided to shake up the
main government scheme for training unemployed adults by cutting its funding
by a third and introducing performance-related pay for the Training and
Enterprise Councils which deliver it.
Mr Portillo's initiative reflects growing scepticism, especially in the
Treasury, about whether the Pounds 762m spent on Training for Work, the
scheme for the adult unemployed, represents good value for money.
It also reflects the belief that too many Tecs are failing to deliver good
enough outcomes for those who go through the scheme. Only 22 per cent of the
120,000 people who completed six-month courses in England and Wales in
1993-94 had a 'positive outcome', meaning either a job, self-employment, or
a move into further education. A further 36 per cent achieved a National
Vocational Qualification.
In order to improve on these figures, and in particular the number going
into jobs, the employment department has decided that from next April all
the Tecs in England and Wales will switch to output-related funding.
That means about 75 per cent of the funds Tecs receive for putting somebody
through Training for Work will be dependent on a positive outcome. At
present more than 70 per cent is paid regardless of what happens to the
trainee after the course.
This will have serious consequences for many of the companies to which Tecs
send their trainees. Officials in both government and the Tecs believe that
too many companies are making too much money from providing courses which do
little to help the unemployed. Many courses concentrate purely on providing
people with NVQs with no connection at all to the jobs market.
An experiment with output-related funding in 12 Tecs has produced
encouraging results. Mr Doug Norris of the North London Tec said that
positive outcomes improved from 20 per cent to 49 per cent as a result of
the trial.
He said: 'The upturn in the economy has helped a bit but it is basically
because we are no longer just paying for a process but for an outcome. It
has allowed me to kick out the training providers who were not getting
results.'
Mr Chris Humphries of the Tec National Council said he would welcome a move
to output funding for all Tecs.
He said: 'This is something which demonstrably works and we have been asking
for this for some time.'
The Tecs are also likely to welcome the fact that trainees in future will be
allowed greater flexibility to do parts of an NVQ rather than the whole
qualification.
But other aspects of Mr Portillo's package may be less welcome to Tecs. The
amount of money available for Training for Work is likely to be cut to less
than Pounds 600m. And poorly performing Tecs may have their contract to
train the adult unemployed removed from them completely.
Some Tec officials also fear that the benefits of the shake-up could be
undermined by any attempt - hinted at by Mr Portillo in his speech to the
Conservative party conference last week - to make receipt of benefit
dependent on taking a training place.
'If anything we should be moving the other way. When training courses are
difficult to get on to trainees are much more enthusiastic about them. If
they are made compulsory the attitude will be terrible,' said one Tec
official.
Such a move might also reverse a marked improvement in attitudes towards
Training for Work among participants. Opinion research with eight groups of
participants by the consultancy Full Employment UK has found a substantial
shift compared with two years ago.
Most participants now say that they are on proper training schemes and
believe that the government is broadly supportive. They also value the fact
that the courses are voluntary.
Eight groups of unemployed people who are not on courses continued to
reflect the negative attitude towards government schemes. Most said that the
courses were just a way of keeping the number of registered unemployed down,
said Mr Peter Ashby of Full Employment UK.
</TEXT>
<XX>
