<HEADLINE>
FT  17 OCT 94 / Tiny rival attacks Branson over cola name
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Marketing Correspondent.
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Richard Branson, the Virgin company chairman who appears to delight in
challenging the supremacy of established organisations such as British
Airways and Coca-Cola, is himself coming under attack from a minnow
competitor.
Mr Ric Huning, a businessman who has been operating a small group of
companies called the Elfin Group from Wales, says he, and not Mr Branson,
was the originator of the idea of a Virgin Cola drink.
Last week, with a great deal of fizz, Mr Branson announced the launch of
Virgin Cola. The drink will initially be distributed mainly through Tesco
supermarkets in the UK.
Mr Huning says he first presented the Cola concept to Virgin in 1992 but
that in January 1993 the organisation rejected the idea.
Virgin has confirmed that the following letter was sent to Mr Huning on 28th
January last year from a Virgin company executive, Mr Craig Dixon: 'Thank
you for your letter of 11th January 1993. Your idea for 'Virgin Cola' looks
very interesting and I am sure it would be a great success.
'However, we are currently concentrating investment on ideas which fit in
with our existing businesses.
'Unfortunately your idea is a little too far removed from those businesses
to be of interest to us. I wish you luck with your endeavours and thank you
for considering Virgin.'
Following this letter Mr Huning said that he started discussions about
manufacturing and marketing Virgin Cola himself.
But then, according to Mr Huning: 'Somebody in the (Virgin) organisation
must have decided somewhere through 1993 that it was a damn good idea and
they should really do it.'
Round one in the battle has already been lost by Mr Huning. In July this
year Virgin gained an interim injunction in the High Court preventing Mr
Huning from using the Virgin Cola name in the UK.
Harbottle &amp; Lewis, Virgin's lawyers in London, said that the letter from Mr
Dixon was 'written by mistake in the middle of an extremely aggressive set
of correspondence' between the firm and Mr Huning.
This correspondence made it clear to Mr Huning that 'if he tried to go ahead
and use this (the Virgin Cola name) we'd come after him,' said Harbottle &amp;
Lewis.
Virgin said Mr Branson had said some years ago that he was thinking of going
into the soft drinks business.
Mr Huning had been told a long time ago that 'Cola wasn't about an idea  -
it was an obvious idea. It was about a formula, and we needed someone to
bring us the formula.'
Mr Huning, who has subsequently fallen out with two of his fellow directors
and seen the collapse of his main trading company, remains undeterred.
He may be prevented from launching Virgin Cola in the UK, but says he is
poised to launch in the US, and is also pressing ahead in Australia and
South Africa.
Mr Huning said this was being done with the backing of a consortium of
international businessmen.
Meanwhile, Virgin is preparing for round two.
The company's lawyers said: 'We are going to take all and any necessary
action against Mr Huning wherever he sees fit to make these allegations.'
</TEXT>
