<HEADLINE>
FT  17 OCT 94 / Chains expect Christmas improvement
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Consumer confidence has shown some improvement recently, and predictions of
a difficult Christmas for retailers may be proved wrong, according to Sir
Malcolm Field, managing director of WH Smith, the newspaper, books and music
group.
His cautiously optimistic views reflect those of a number of retailers which
have reported results recently. WH Smith experienced a slow midsummer period
but things improved in late summer and early autumn.
That partly reflected the arrival of cooler weather after the July heatwave,
and some improvement in sentiment.
He said: 'There is some underlying improvement in confidence, but the
question is, is it sustainable? I think Christmas will be good, but only the
best chains will win. You have to fight for every sale these days.'
Sir Malcolm added that he often felt official retail sales figures did not
reflect what was happening on the high street 'I sometimes wonder who is
contributing to them.'
Among other retailers, Storehouse - the clothing group which includes BHS
and Mothercare - issued a trading statement earlier this month saying that
sales for the six months to October were expected to be up by about 10 per
cent. Next, the fashion retailer, last month reported sales 13 per cent
ahead of last year.
Body Shop, the natural cosmetics retailer, said on Thursday that underlying
UK sales in the six months to the end of August were up 5 per cent -
compared with a 5 per cent fall in the same period last year.
However, Kingfisher, which includes the B&amp;Q, Woolworths, Comet and Superdrug
chains, said conditions remained tough, particularly in the DIY and
electrical goods sectors.
Competition on price also remains tough, holding inflation down.
