<HEADLINE>
FT  17 OCT 94 / Analysts delve into lucky dip of retail statistics
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILLIAN TETT and NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Easy profits are out, the canny consumer is king. That is the main message
from the retail sector as it prepares to enter the crucial Christmas trading
season.
But the question that will be raised this week, as a new set of retail data
is published, is how far this cautious consumer mentality is affecting sales
 -and with it the tools used to measure retail behaviour.
For with consumers adjusting to a new low-inflation environment, and the
nature of the retail sector itself changing, making sense of the various
sets of consumer data on offer is becoming an increasingly complex task.
For example, the official retail sales data, to be published by the Central
Statistical Office on Thursday, suggest that retail sales grew steadily this
year on the back of the recovery amid heavy price competition, but fell back
in August.
Some analysts suspect this dip was due to the summer holiday. But others say
that it points to a broader slowdown, not least because the Confederation of
British Industry's survey of distributive traders, published tomorrow, has
recently been adopting a more sober tone.
The CSO's consumer spending data, which is published on a quarterly basis,
is even more downbeat. It suggests sales of non-durable goods started to
drop as early as the spring.
This, however, would appear to be at odds with the Bank of England's data on
the level of notes and coins in circulation, previously a good guide to
consumer spending. These have been showing strong growth this year.
Meanwhile consumer credit data, published last week, put borrowing at a
record high.
For some economists this implies that there might be shortcomings in the
official statistics, not least because many retailers say their experiences
differ from the findings in the official data.
Mr Harry Moore, chief executive of Co-operative Retail Services, which has a
variety of retail outlets including supermarkets and department stores, said
he had little confidence in the figures.
He said: 'I often ask myself where the devil do they get these figures from?
I can't make head or tail of them. There is virtually no food inflation, for
example, but we are not aware of any consumer confidence.'
Mr Clive Vaughan, retail analyst at Verdict, the market research group, has
been puzzled and frustrated by the data in recent months.
However, economists such as Mr Chris Dillow of Nomura Research, disagree. He
said: 'I think the retail data is pretty good.' The signals all appeared to
be pointing to a temporary slowdown in spending as the tax increases took
effect.
Nevertheless, the real problem that may be confronting economists is that
tracking consumer behaviour is particularly difficult because of broader
changes occurring in this recovery. On the one hand, the nature of the
retail sector is changing as large retailers gain market share at the
expense of smaller ones and more retailers become multisector outlets.
Meanwhile, as last week's inflation data showed, underlying inflation is at
a record low, affecting retailers' perceptions and consumer behaviour.
The CSO collects its retail sales figures from about 5,000 retailers, of
which the bigger retailers generally account for most overall sales. Mr
Philip Gooding, CSO statistician, insists that the survey is representative.
But Mr Richard Brown, deputy director-general of the Chambers of Commerce,
said: 'The official data do seem to hide the situation of smaller
retailers.'
Mr Ian Shepherdson, of Midland Global Markets, said this might explain the
recent puzzling trends in food retailsales, which were showing annual volume
growth of more than 5 per cent, far higher than other sectors.
This might reflect the fact that big chains have been gaining market share
because of supermarket price wars, he said. 'The CSO is almost certainly
capturing the entire gains in market share by the large retailers, but it
may be missing some of the small retailers' losses,' he said.
Analysis is made even harder because the CSO collects only a limited
commodity breakdown.
But if the official retail sales data are faced with the problem of shifting
market shares, surveys such as the CBI series face other problems.
Mr Sudhir Junankar, the CBI's associate economic director, believes low
inflation may lead some shopkeepers to understate their sales volumes
because heavy discounting leaves retailers with a particularly gloomy
impression of business.
In the long term, Mr Junankar says, the CBI survey - which covers 15,000
outlets - and the retail sales data have tended to track each other. But
observers such as Mr May remain cynical. 'Our feeling is that the CBI tends
to get it wrong nine times out of 10,' he said.
This discounting environment may also be affecting other series. Most
analysts believe the recent rise in the level of notes and coins in
circulation reflects the fact that low interest rates and inflation make it
more attractive to hold cash. Meanwhile, the recent surge in consumer credit
may reflect the fact that consumers are taking advantage of cheap financing.
Faced with this problem, most analysts conclude that the best solution to
the discrepancies is the most obvious - to use a basket of indicators.
As Mr David Mackie of JP Morgan points out, although the data might
sometimes seem to be at odds, the sheer variety represents something of a
luxury.
Spending on services represents almost half of consumer spending but data on
this sector is limited. Consequently the biggest mystery that may be
confronting economists as they try to make sense of consumer behaviour this
autumn may not be what is happening in the retail sector  - but what is
going on in all the other non-retail areas as well.
Additional reporting by Neil Buckley
</TEXT>
<XX>
