<HEADLINE>
FT  17 OCT 94 / Asia: Kim Jong-il to be named leader soon - Public
appearance in Pyongyang points to his assumption of presidency
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN BURTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SEOUL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Kim Jong-il's first public appearance in almost three months signals he
will soon be formally named as North Korea's new leader. Mr Kim attended a
memorial ceremony yesterday in Pyongyang, marking the end of the 100-day
mourning period for his father, the late President Kim Il-sung.
Analysts in Seoul believe the end of the mourning period will clear the way
for Mr Kim, last seen in public at his father's funeral on July 20, to
assume the presidency of the country and head the ruling Korean Workers'
Party in the next few weeks.
Mr Kim, who appeared somewhat haggard, was flanked by leading members of the
ruling hierarchy in an apparent show of unity. The absence of Mr Kim from
public view has led to speculation that his assumption of power may be
encountering internal opposition.
However, analysts believe he is already firmly in control of the government
and has avoided formally taking power during the mourning period because it
would appear unseemly, immediately after his father's death.
'Since the death of Kim Il-sung, there has been no sign of a power struggle
in North Korea, including a conflict with the military. Moreover, there are
no rival candidates at present who can compete against Kim Jong-il,' said Mr
Hideshi Takesada, a researcher at the National Institute for Defence Studies
in Japan.
'Kim Jong-il has been consolidating family loyalty by recruiting relatives
and classmates to major official positions. Over 90 per cent of officials
with the rank above chairmen in the party and state administration council
are those appointed by Kim Jong-il,' explained Mr Kil Jeong-woo, director of
policy studies at the Research Institute for National Unification in Seoul.
He also 'seems to have secured absolute support from the major figures in
charge of the three military organisations,' which have been mentioned as
the main source of possible opposition to his rule.
One sign of continued stability has been North Korea's negotiations with the
US over its nuclear programme, which have shown some signs of progress in
the past week. But weekend discussions in Geneva remained stuck over North
Korea's refusal to accept international inspection of undeclared suspect
nuclear facilities.
The talks, begun by Kim Il-sung, have shown little sign of deviation since
his death. 'Policy making in North Korea is the product of team work among
leading figures; Kim Il-sung's death did not have any drastic impact on
security strategy,' said Mr Gunter Unterbeck, a former East German diplomat
in Pyongyang.
However, Mr Kim may be forced to share more decision-making with the top
leadership than his father did.
</TEXT>
