<HEADLINE>
FT  17 OCT 94 / Personal rivalries hamper Slovak struggle to form a
coalition: Meciar is finding it difficult to attract political partners
Boland
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VINCENT BOLAND
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Two weeks after its first general election as an independent country,
Slovakia's byzantine political scene has yet to yield a new government.
Coalition talks among the seven parties that won seats in parliament have
foundered over long-standing personality rivalries concerning the country's
president, Mr Michal Kovac.
Mr Vladimir Meciar, whose party got most seats in the election on September
30 and October 1, is almost certain to become the country's prime minister
for a third time. His Movement for a Democratic Slovakia (HZDS) has 61 seats
in the 150-member Slovak national council, more than three times as many as
its nearest rival.
But so far it has failed to attract any coalition partners. Talks between
HZDS and the moderate Christian Democrats (KDH), which won 17 seats, have
stalled, despite Mr Meciar's offer of the foreign affairs and transport
ministries.
Negotiations with the second biggest party, the Democratic Left (SDL), which
consists mainly of former communists, are also in limbo. Ms Brigita
Schmognerova, a deputy prime minister in the outgoing government
representing the SDL, says the party is 'still open' to joining with HZDS
but that 'the personality of Mr Meciar is a problem'.
Analysts say the biggest obstacle to an HZDS-led coalition is the party's
threat to remove President Kovac from office. He was instrumental in ousting
Mr Meciar as prime minister in March, amid allegations that the HZDS leader
was 'abusing' the privatisation process.
Mr Meciar has not forgotten the insult, and in his campaign speeches he
vowed revenge. But Mr Kovac retains strong support among moderate Slovak
parties.
HZDS could form a government immediately by entering a coalition with the
extreme right-wing Slovak National Party and governing with the support of
the socialist Union of Slovak Workers. The three parties have a combined 83
seats.
If no agreement can be reached between HZDS and more mainstream parties,
such a coalition is likely to assume office, ushering in a period of
instability.
If, as seems likely, HZDS dominates the new government, it will seek to
retain control of key ministries, such as finance and privatisation. This
could result in a major shift in privatisation policy, a central plank of
the outgoing administration's economic reforms. The departing prime
minister, Mr Jozef Moravcik, revived voucher privatisation, in which Slovak
citizens buy coupons they can exchange for shares in state companies. Over
1m Slovaks have registered to take part in the programme.
Senior HZDS officials have indicated the programme would be curtailed if the
party came to power, with many enterprises scheduled for sell-off staying in
state hands.
Any government's room for manoeuvre in reshaping economic policy is limited.
It will have to abide by tight constraints on public spending imposed in
July by the International Monetary Fund in return for a Dollars 168m (Pounds
112m) standby loan. This will leave little scope for wage rises or higher
pensions, which Mr Meciar promised during the election campaign. 'Whatever
the new government, it will want to retain its access to international
capital markets,' says a western economic adviser in Bratislava.
This is why foreign investors are sanguine about Slovakia's economic
potential, despite the political uncertainty. In a report on the country in
August, ING Securities urged investors to 'look beyond the rhetoric' of
politicians and focus on economic realities. 'We are fundamentally positive
towards Slovakia,' says Mr Jean-Christophe Ganz, manager of ING Bank's
branch in Bratislava.
Slovakia's gross domestic product has expanded 4.4 per cent in the first
half of 1994, reversing four years of decline. Foreign reserves have climbed
from Dollars 415.3m at the end of 1993 to Dollars 1.38bn on September 28;
inflation is down from an annual 16.4 per cent in January to 13.5 per cent
in July. Unemployment remains high at 14.5 per cent.
If things begin to go wrong for the new government there is concern it might
seek scapegoats among Slovakia's 560,000-strong ethnic Hungarian minority.
Though they have 17 seats in parliament, ethnic Hungarians remain outside
the political mainstream. It is to areas such as this, as much as to his
attitude to investors, that observers will look for evidence that Mr Meciar
has learned lessons from his short break in Slovakia's political wilderness.
</TEXT>
