<HEADLINE>
FT  17 OCT 94 / Finns vote 'Yes' to EU in first of Nordic ballots
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HUGH CARNEGY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   HELSINKI
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Finland voted yesterday to join the European Union in the first of three
Nordic ballots that could enlarge membership of the EU from 12 to 16.
The result, showing a Yes victory by 53 per cent to 47 per cent, was
welcomed by Mr Esko Aho, the prime minister. The turnout of 74 per cent was
slightly higher than the turnout in the last general election.
However, the margin was less than pro-EU supporters had hoped for, and fell
below Austria's Yes vote of more than 66 per cent in June.
In Brussels, Mr Hans van den Broek, the EU commissioner for external
affairs, said he hoped the referendum result would help win a Yes vote in
Sweden and Norway.
In both those countries opposition to membership has been much stronger than
in Finland and Austria.
The Social Democratic leadership in Sweden and the Labour party government
in Norway looked to Finland for added momentum to their campaigns for a Yes
vote. The Finnish vote was scheduled first in the hope of achieving a Nordic
domino effect.
In Sweden, which votes on November 13, most polls have shown a slight but
unsteady lead for the Yes side since the summer. In Norway, where the
referendum is on November 28, the No camp holds a solid lead.
But a weekend opinion poll for the first time showed a clear majority for
membership based on a Yes in both Finland and Sweden. The poll showed 46 per
cent in favour to 41 per cent against - a turnaround from last month when
the same poll showed a No lead of 47 per cent against 39 per cent.
The majority of Finland's political establishment and business leaders
argued that membership would underpin the Finnish economy, which this year
has started to recover from a crippling recession that saw output shrink by
13 per cent between 1991 and 1994 and unemployment rise to almost 20 per
cent of the workforce. Finland's parliament must ratify yesterday's
referendum result by a two-thirds majority before the country can join the
Union as planned on January 1 next year, but this is not expected to prove
an obstacle.
</TEXT>
