<PROFILE>_AN-EJPAHADYFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>941015
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  15 OCT 94 / Pink Snow (8): Cross-country skiing
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Why should you want to haul yourself about on skis while the ski lift could
do the work? Why plod through the snow with the brakes on when you could be
swooping like a bird amid the peaks?
If you are asking these questions, you have never tried cross-country
skiing.
Sir Norman Foster, the architect, has been an enthusiastic cross-country
skier for more than a decade and has more-or-less completed the switch from
downhill.
He says that cross-country skiing is easy. 'It's fantastic at every level.
It works for little old ladies who go out for a walk on skis to the most
incredible athletes in streamlined clothes.'
Before you even start, you feel the difference.
The boots are like running shoes and the skis weigh ounces. On day one, with
zero technique and on the flat, each normal walking step takes you two
metres.
After a week, you can climb into woodland off-piste and enjoy the
exhilaration of being in mountain peace that mechanised Alpine skiers do not
know exists.
Choose your resort carefully. Few people can cross-country ski from dawn to
dusk. Make sure that you have the options of shopping, dining, skating,
curling, sleigh riding, hot pool swimming, dog-sledding, ice fishing or just
strolling.
Then rediscover all the things that could be done in winter before they were
buried by the avalanche of Alpine skiing.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P7999 Amusement and Recreation, NEC.
</IN>
